Introduction

This notebook focuses on collecting, processing, interpreting, and making predictions on housing data. With the noticeable and problematic increase in housing prices, including buyers and renters, this notebook aims to fully understand the difference between the median income and the average housing prices.

Factors To Address

There are many factors to consider when looking at the differences between income and the median sale price of houses listed on Zillow. While the affects of inflation do impact both the housing market and median income data, it can make the difference between the two seem larger than the actual value.

Another factor to address is the difference in median income and housing prices per location. These two values are going to vary and may be more or less favorable depending on how the two values are effected. In this analysis, the data as a whole is going to be analyzed, meaning that the average between all locations main focus with the specific locations being less prioritized.

Impact Of This Analysis

Learning more about the relationship between the median housing price and income is important for learning the true danger that the drastic increase in housing prices can cause. It helps shed light on the problems with accessibility to housing that is currently happening and that is continuing to grow. This can help inform those who can regulate these prices and help aid the issue by providing an accurate analysis of the data. For those who are looking to buy or sell a home, there is also the added benefit of understanding the differences between income and housing price by location. With different regions changing at different rates, it might help guide people to choosing a smart location to live and purchase any sort of housing.

Data Collection and Processing

The first step of the data analysis process involves reading a CSV file named median_sale_price.csv into a pandas DataFrame. Next, we refine the data by removing unnecessary columns: "SizeRank," "RegionType," "RegionID," and "StateName." We then ensure data integrity by dropping any rows with missing values. To facilitate easier access and analysis, the "RegionName" column is set as the DataFrame's index, representing various regions. The column names, initially representing dates, are converted from strings to datetime objects and reassigned to the DataFrame. The DataFrame is then transposed, so the dates become row indices and the regions become columns. Finally, we verify the transformation by displaying the first eight rows of the modified DataFrame using head(8).

Median Sale Price

This data downloaded from Zillow's housing price database is the median income of all house types. This is the raw data, unprocessed by Zillow beforehand. This data is sporadic and highly effected by seasonal changes and inflation. From there we can remove the unnecessary data, clean up the datapoints, and format it to make it easy to graph and manipulate. This is the main data that we will be processing and analyzing.

Adjusting For Inflation

Using the United States monthly inflation data, we can calculate annual inflation rate using the monthly rate. This can be applied to scale the dataset and create a rate of housing price increase that is unaffected by inflation.

In[5]:
# function to turn monthly data into annual inflation data
def calculate_annual_inflation(row):
    # converting the percentage data to decimal data
    monthly_rates_decimal = [1 + (rate / 100) for rate in row]
    # creating the product
    annual_rate = np.prod(monthly_rates_decimal)
    # converts the inflation rate from decimal back to percentage
    annual_inflation_rate = (annual_rate - 1) * 100
    return annual_inflation_rate

# importing inflation data
inflation_path = "Final/inflation_data.csv"
inflation_df = pd.read_csv(inflation_path)

# removing unnecessary columns and adding columns to create annual data
inflation_df.drop(["HALF1", "HALF2"], axis=1, inplace=True)
inflation_df["Annual"] = inflation_df.iloc[:, 1:].apply(calculate_annual_inflation, axis=1)

# creating a value to scale the years of the median and income dataframe by centered around 2008
# this means the actual dollar value is in terms of 2008 data
inflation_df['CumulativeInflation'] = (1 + inflation_df['Annual'] / 100).cumprod()
base_year = 2008
base_cpi = inflation_df[inflation_df['Year'] == base_year]['CumulativeInflation'].values[0]
inflation_df['CumulativeInflation'] /= base_cpi

Inflation Adjustment

Here we can create our normalized dataset and replace the data we were working with before. Doing this will allow us to now have any bias from the inflation rate that may change the values of certain analysis points later.

In[8]:
# creating copies to have normailized dataframes seperate but will use exclusively
normalized_mean_df = mean_df.copy()
normalized_median_df = median_df.copy()
normalized_income_df = income_df.copy()

# index of inflation data by year
cumulative_inflation_dict = inflation_df.set_index('Year')['CumulativeInflation'].to_dict()

# although not used, we will normalized the mean_df incase we ever want to work with mean data in future
for index in mean_df.index:
    # removing uncessary columns
    for col in mean_df.columns[2:]:
        # gets the year from the column
        if isinstance(col, pd.Timestamp):
            year = col.year
            # normalizes value based on current year
            normalized_mean_df.at[index, col] = mean_df.at[index, col] / cumulative_inflation_dict[year]

# same process for median dataframe
for index in median_df.index:
    for col in median_df.columns[2:]: 
        if isinstance(col, pd.Timestamp):
            year = col.year
            # normalize values based on year
            normalized_median_df.at[index, col] = median_df.at[index, col] / cumulative_inflation_dict[year]

# finally we can normalize the income as well
for col in income_df.columns:
    # gets year for data point
    if isinstance(col, pd.Timestamp):
        year = col.year
        # updates value based on year
        normalized_income_df[col] = income_df[col] / cumulative_inflation_dict[year]

# updating useful dataframes to keep variable names consistent
median_df = normalized_median_df
income_df = normalized_income_df

These plots here show the smoothing of the median sale price by decomposing the data and removing any seasonal factors. You can see the jumpiness of the plot caused by the data, this can be factored in to our analysis, but separating the data will become useful.

In[11]:
# feature extraction for predictions



# getting year month and quarter
median_df['Year'] = median_df.index.year
median_df['Month'] = median_df.index.month
median_df['Quarter'] = median_df.index.quarter

# using seasonal decompose to find the trend in the data (smooth average basically)
result = seasonal_decompose(median_df['Average'], model='additive', period=12)
median_df['SMA'] = result.trend
median_df['Seasonal'] = result.seasonal
median_df['SSDA'] = median_df['Average'].rolling(window=12).std()
# create lag points from previous data for prediction
median_df['Lag10'] = median_df['SMA'].shift(10)
median_df['Lag20'] = median_df['SMA'].shift(20)

# removing any unused columns
median_df.dropna(inplace=True)

# plotting the data of smooth trend and extra data from the seasonal decompose
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(median_df['Average'], label='Housing Prices')
plt.plot(median_df['SMA'], label='Smooth Average', linestyle='--')
plt.title('Housing Prices with Moving Averages')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Price')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

result.plot()
plt.show()

Predicting Future Outcomes

Now we can start working towards building a model using the data that can predict future outcomes. This will be beneficial for the future when housing prices for future dates can be looked at. Using the features extracted from the dataset, we can train a model using the LinearRegression class. The data is split by year and the outputs of the prediction can be shown below. As you can see, the model is fairly accurate and accounting for seasonal trends.

In[13]:
# setting up training and testing data
train_data = median_df[median_df['Year'] <= 2018]
test_data = median_df[median_df['Year'] > 2018]

# selecting certain feature columns and for both the testing and training data
features = ['Year', 'Month', 'Quarter', 'Seasonal', 'SMA', 'SSDA', 'Lag10', 'Lag20']
X_train = train_data[features]
y_train = train_data['Average']
X_test = test_data[features]
y_test = test_data['Average']

# linear regression model
model = LinearRegression()
# training model on training data
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# creating predictions on test data
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# finding the mean squared error between the y-test and prediction
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
rmse = np.sqrt(mse)
print(f'RMSE: {rmse}')

# plotting data
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
plt.plot(train_data.index, train_data['Average'], label='Train Data')
plt.plot(test_data.index, y_test, label='Test Data')
plt.plot(test_data.index, y_pred, label='Predicted Data', linestyle='--')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Average')
plt.title('Actual vs Predicted Values')
plt.show()

RMSE: 6280.5587762192345

A Quick Look At Location Specific Data

These values are going to be similar, so the data computed using the average of all locations is generalizable. But this is a factor that was left out as the mean of the locations would provide a good comparison. With this in mind, there were a few locations that were significantly higher or lower compared to the rest. The bar graph below represents the difference in rate of change of the income and housing data by location. This is represented in decimal form, so the range of the data is almost 3.5%. Again this is caused by outliers in the data, so the factor that is has can be mostly ignored as this is a more general analysis of the data, but it is interesting to see the differences.

In[16]:
# sampling data to create monthly values for income
income_df_monthly = income_df.resample('M').ffill()

# calculate the monthly rate of change for income
income_df_monthly['ROC'] = income_df_monthly['Income'].pct_change()

# calculate the monthly rate of change for the different locations
location_columns = [col for col in median_df.columns if ',' in col]
rate_change_df = median_df[location_columns].pct_change()

# restrict the end dates for both dataframes
end_date = '2022-12-31'
rate_change_df = rate_change_df.loc[:end_date]
income_df_monthly = income_df_monthly.loc[:end_date]

# make sure that the data values both cover the same timespan
common_dates = rate_change_df.index.intersection(income_df_monthly.index)
rate_change_df = rate_change_df.loc[common_dates]
income_df_monthly = income_df_monthly.loc[common_dates]

# create average income rate of change for the different locations
avg_income_rate_change = income_df_monthly['ROC'].mean()
avg_house_price_rate_change = rate_change_df.mean()

# find the difference between the average rate of change in income and house prices
diff_avg_rate_change = avg_house_price_rate_change - avg_income_rate_change

# get indices of both max differences in income and housing rate of change
max_diff_location = diff_avg_rate_change.idxmax()
max_diff_value = diff_avg_rate_change.max()

# get indices of both min differences in income and housing rate of change
min_diff_location = diff_avg_rate_change.idxmin()
min_diff_value = diff_avg_rate_change.min()

print(f"Location with the minimum difference in average rate of change: {min_diff_location}, Difference: {min_diff_value}")
print(f"Location with the maximum difference in average rate of change: {max_diff_location}, Difference: {max_diff_value}")
print(f"The range of the data between the minimum and maximum average rate of change: {max_diff_value - min_diff_value}")

# average rate of change differences as a bar plot
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
diff_avg_rate_change.plot(kind='bar')
plt.xlabel('Location')
plt.ylabel('Difference in Average Rate of Change')
plt.title('Difference in Average Rate of Change: Median Income vs. House Prices')
plt.xticks([])

Conclusion

This notebook provided a comprehensive analysis of housing data, focusing on the relationship between median income and average housing prices. By examining various factors such as inflation and regional disparities, we highlighted the significant differences in the rate of change between income and house prices. Our findings reveal that certain locations experience more pronounced discrepancies, which can inform policymakers and stakeholders in addressing housing affordability challenges. The visualization and statistical methods employed here offer a clear picture of the current housing market dynamics, aiding in future decision-making processes.

This notebook as a whole provides a comprehensive analysis of the relationship between housing data and income data in the United States. We were able to account for inflation and show an unbiased analysis, even creating a predictive model if future data needs to be calculated. Hopefully this data is helpful for informing the public on the danger of increasing home prices, as well as provide an in depth look at specific locations and trends in the case where any regulations or policies are put in place to combat this increase.
